# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: protein-folding
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] AlphaFold 1 (2018) placed first in the overall rankings of the 13th Critical Assessment of Structure Prediction (CASP) in December 2018.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] It was particularly successful at predicting the most accurate structures for targets rated as most difficult by the competition organizers, where no existing template structures were available from proteins with partially similar sequences.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] AlphaFold 2 (2020) repeated this placement in the CASP14 competition in November 2020.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] It achieved a level of accuracy much higher than any other entry.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] It scored above 90 on CASP's global distance test (GDT) for approximately two-thirds of the proteins, a test measuring the similarity between a computationally predicted structure and the experimentally determined structure, where 100 represents a complete match.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] The inclusion of metagenomic data has improved the quality of the prediction of multiple sequence alignments.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] One of the biggest sources of the training data was the custom-built Big Fantastic Database of 65,983,866 protein families, represented as multiple sequence alignments and Hidden Markov models, covering 2,204,359,010 protein sequences from reference databases, metagenomes, and metatranscriptomes.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] AlphaFold 2's results at CASP14 were described as "astounding" and "transformational".
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] However, some researchers noted that the accuracy was insufficient for a third of its predictions, and that it did not reveal the underlying mechanism or rules of protein folding for the protein folding problem, which remains unsolved.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] Despite this, the technical achievement was widely recognized.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] On 15 July 2021, the AlphaFold 2 paper was published in *Nature* as an advance access publication alongside open source software and a searchable database of species proteomes.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] As of November 2025, the paper had been cited nearly 43,000 times.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] AlphaFold 3 was announced on 8 May 2024.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] It can predict the structure of complexes created by proteins with DNA, RNA, various ligands, and ions.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] The new prediction method shows a minimum 50% improvement in accuracy for protein interactions with other molecules compared to existing methods.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] Proteins consist of chains of amino acids which spontaneously fold to form the three dimensional (3-D) structures of the proteins.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] The 3-D structure is necessary to understanding the biological function of the protein.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] Protein structures can be determined experimentally through techniques such as X-ray crystallography, cryo-electron microscopy and nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR), which are all expensive and time-consuming.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] Such efforts, using the experimental methods, have identified the structures of about 170,000 proteins over the last 60 years, while there are over 200 million known proteins across all life forms.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] Over the years, researchers have applied numerous computational methods to predict the 3D structures of proteins from their amino acid sequences, accuracy of such methods in best possible scenario is close to experimental techniques (NMR) by the use of homology modeling based on molecular evolution.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] CASP, which was launched in 1994 to challenge the scientific community to produce their best protein structure predictions, found that GDT scores of only about 40 out of 100 can be achieved for the most difficult proteins by 2016.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] AlphaFold started competing in the 2018 CASP using an artificial intelligence (AI) deep learning technique.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] DeepMind is known to have trained the program on over 170,000 protein structures from the Protein Data Bank, a public repository of protein sequences and structures.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] The program uses a form of attention network, a deep learning technique that focuses on having the AI identify parts of a larger problem, then piece it together to obtain the overall solution.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] The overall training was conducted on processing power between 100 and 200 GPUs.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] The 2020 version of the program (**AlphaFold 2**, 2020) is significantly different from the original version that won CASP 13 in 2018, according to the team at DeepMind.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] AlphaFold 1 used a number of separately trained modules to produce a guide potential, which was then combined with a physics-based energy potential.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] AlphaFold 2 replaced this with a system of interconnected sub-networks, forming a single, differentiable, end-to-end model based on pattern recognition.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] This model was trained in an integrated manner.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] After the neural network's prediction converges, a final refinement step applies local physical constraints using energy minimization based on the AMBER force field.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] This step only slightly adjusts the predicted structure.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] Internally these refinement transformations contain layers that have the effect of bringing relevant data together and filtering out irrelevant data (the "attention mechanism") for these relationships, in a context-dependent way, learned from training data.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] The output of these iterations then informs the final structure prediction module, which also uses transformers, and is itself then iterated.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] In an example presented by DeepMind, the structure prediction module achieved a correct topology for the target protein on its first iteration, scored as having a GDT_TS of 78, but with a large number (90%) of stereochemical violations – i.e. unphysical bond angles or lengths.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] With subsequent iterations the number of stereochemical violations fell.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] By the third iteration the GDT_TS of the prediction was approaching 90, and by the eighth iteration the number of stereochemical violations was approaching zero.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] The training data was originally restricted to single peptide chains.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] However, the October 2021 update, named AlphaFold-Multimer, included protein complexes in its training data.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] DeepMind stated this update succeeded about 70% of the time at accurately predicting protein-protein interactions.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] Announced on 8 May 2024, **AlphaFold 3** was co-developed by Google DeepMind and Isomorphic Labs, both subsidiaries of Alphabet.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] AlphaFold 3 is not limited to proteins, as it can also predict the structures of protein complexes with DNA, RNA, post-translational modifications and selected ligands and ions.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] AlphaFold 3 introduces the "Pairformer," a deep learning architecture inspired by the transformer, which is considered similar to, but simpler than, the Evoformer used in AlphaFold 2.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] The Pairformer module's initial predictions are refined by a diffusion model.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] This model begins with a cloud of atoms and iteratively refines their positions, guided by the Pairformer's output, to generate a 3D representation of the molecular structure.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] The AlphaFold server was created to provide free access to AlphaFold 3 for non-commercial research.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] As of November 2025, the AlphaFold 3 research paper has been directly cited more than 9,000 times.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] In December 2018, DeepMind's AlphaFold placed first in the overall rankings of the 13th Critical Assessment of Techniques for Protein Structure Prediction (CASP).
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] The program was particularly successfully predicting the most accurate structure for targets rated as the most difficult by the competition organisers, where no existing template structures were available from proteins with a partially similar sequence.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] AlphaFold gave the best prediction for 25 out of 43 protein targets in this class, achieving a median score of 58.9 on the CASP's global distance test (GDT) score, ahead of 52.5 and 52.4 by the two next best-placed teams, who were also using deep learning to estimate contact distances.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] Overall, across all targets, AlphaFold 1 achieved a GDT score of 68.5.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] In January 2020, implementations and illustrative code of AlphaFold 1 was released open-source on GitHub. but, as stated in the "Read Me" file on that website: "This code can't be used to predict structure of an arbitrary protein sequence.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] It can be used to predict structure only on the CASP13 dataset (links below).
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] The feature generation code is tightly coupled to our internal infrastructure as well as external tools, hence we are unable to open-source it." Therefore, in essence, the code deposited is not suitable for general use but only for the CASP13 proteins.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] The company has not announced plans to make their code publicly available as of 5 March 2021.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] In November 2020, DeepMind's new version, AlphaFold 2, won CASP14.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] Overall, AlphaFold 2 made the best prediction for 88 out of the 97 targets.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] In 2018 AlphaFold 1 had only reached this level of accuracy in two of all of its predictions.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] 88% of predictions in the 2020 competition had a GDT_TS score of more than 80.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] On the group of targets classed as the most difficult, AlphaFold 2 achieved a median score of 87.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] 76% of predictions achieved better than 3 Å, and 46% had a C-alpha atom RMS accuracy better than 2 Å, with a median RMS deviation in its predictions of 2.1 Å for a set of overlapped CA atoms.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] AlphaFold 2 also achieved an accuracy in modelling surface side chains described as "really really extraordinary".
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] To further validate AlphaFold 2, the conference organizers approached four leading experimental groups working on structures they found particularly challenging and had been unable to determine.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] In all four cases the three-dimensional models produced by AlphaFold 2 were sufficiently accurate to determine structures of these proteins by molecular replacement.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] These included target T1100 (Af1503), a small membrane protein studied by experimentalists for ten years.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] Of the three structures that AlphaFold 2 had the least success in predicting, one was an unusual multidomain complex consisting of 52 identical copies of the same domain.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] For all targets with a single domain, excluding only one very large protein and the two structures determined by NMR, AlphaFold 2 achieved a GDT_TS score of over 80.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] In 2022, DeepMind did not enter CASP15, but most of the entrants used AlphaFold or tools incorporating AlphaFold.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] AlphaFold 2 scoring more than 90 in CASP's global distance test (GDT) is a great achievement in computational biology.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] Nobel Prize winner and structural biologist Venki Ramakrishnan called the result "a stunning advance on the protein folding problem", adding that "It has occurred decades before many people in the field would have predicted.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] AlphaFold 2's success received wide media attention.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] News pieces appeared in the science press, such as *Nature*, *Science*, *MIT Technology Review*, and *New Scientist*, and the story was covered by national newspapers.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] A frequent theme was the ability to predict protein structures based on the constituent amino acid sequence, expected to have benefits in the life sciences—accelerating drug discovery and enabling better understanding of diseases.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] Some have noted that even a perfect answer to the protein *prediction* problem still leaves questions about the protein *folding* problem (and thus protein dynamics)—understanding in detail how the folding process actually occurs in nature (and how sometimes they can also misfold).
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] In 2023, Demis Hassabis and John Jumper won the Breakthrough Prize in Life Sciences as well as the Albert Lasker Award for Basic Medical Research for their management of the AlphaFold project.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] Hassabis and Jumper proceeded to win the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 2024 for their work on "protein structure prediction" with David Baker of the University of Washington.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] Open access to source code of several AlphaFold versions (excluding AlphaFold 3) has been provided by DeepMind in 2022 after requests from the scientific community.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] The source code and weights of AlphaFold 3 were made available for non-commercial use to the scientific community upon request in November 2024.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] It became publicly available in February 2025, still retaining the non-commercial restriction.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] A number of AlphaFold clones have also been published, mostly with permissive license terms.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] Clones for AlphaFold3 include ByteDance's Protenix (Apache 2.0 License), AlQuraishi Laboratory's OpenFold-3 (MIT license), and Boltz-1/2 (MIT license).
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] There are also clones for older versions, though they became less relevant with the open-source release of AlphaFold 1 and 2 source codes.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] Still relevant are models, both open- and closed-source, that include modifications to the AlphaFold architecture.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] For AlphaFold 2, a notable example is ESMFold from Meta, which replaces the multiple sequence alignment with the latent space of a protein language model.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] Open-source tools that complement AlphaFold have also been made.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] One well-cited example is ColabFold, which uses MMseqs2 instead of HHblits to speed up the sequence search, allowing the AlphaFold pipelines to run quickly on Google Colab.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] The **AlphaFold Protein Structure Database** (AFDB), a joint project between AlphaFold and EMBL-EBI, was launched on July 22, 2021.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] At launch, the database contained AlphaFold 1-predicted models for nearly the complete UniProt proteome of humans and 20 model organisms, totaling over 365,000 proteins.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] The database does not include proteins with fewer than 16 or more than 2700 amino acid residues, but for humans they are available in the whole batch file.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] AlphaFold's initial goal (as of early 2022) was to expand the database to cover most of the UniRef90 set, which contains over 100 million proteins.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] As of May 15, 2022, the database contained 992,316 predictions.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] In July 2021, UniProt-KB and InterPro has been updated to show AlphaFold predictions when available.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] On July 28, 2022, the team uploaded to the database the structures of around 200 million proteins from 1 million species, covering nearly every known protein on the planet.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] The number as of 2024 is 214 million, with 26 million being duplicates (exact sequence matches) of another protein in the database.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] The predicted structures can differ significantly between duplicates.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] As of 2025, the AFDB uses AlphaFold 2 for its predictions.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] All structures produced remain monomeric, but multimeric structures produced by other databases are linked on the page through the 3D-Beacons API.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] Foldseek, which provides fast and accurate structure searches, is also integrated.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] Information from AlphaMissense (a tool that uses AlphaFold to predict the outcome of missense mutations) is also integrated.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] AlphaFill adds cofactors to AlphaFold models where appropriate.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] This is achieved by searching the Protein Data Bank for similar structures and transplanting cofactors to analogous positions.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] TmAlphaFold docks AlphaFold models to biological membranes, similar to what OPM does for PDB structures.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] AFTM uses AlphaFold models to identify transmembrane regions in human proteins, similar to what PDBTM does for PDB structures.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] ChannelsDB 2.0 uses PDB or AlphaFill models to calculate the pathway a molecule may take to reach an enzyme's active site or to reach another side of a transmembrane pore.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] The AFDB is not updated with UniProt sequences changes.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] AlphaSync keeps the AFDB in sync with UniProt entry changes, generating updated structures, residue-level features and contacts.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] It tries to use an AFDB entry for the exact updated sequence when available and run AlphaFold 2 independently otherwise.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] It fills in AFDB's blank for large (> 2,700 aa) proteins and proteins with special FASTA characters such as B, Z, U or X.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] The Encyclopedia of Domains (TED) applies the domain-recognition method from CATH database to 188 million unique structures from the AFDB, identifying nearly 365 million domains, which is 100 million more than what sequence-based methods could identify.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] The Evolutionary Classification of Protein Domains database (ECOD) assigns ECOD classifications to all SwissProt proteins in AFDB.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] isoform.io is a database of AlphaFold2-generated structures of proposed splice isoforms in the human genome.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] It includes information from 237,275 human transcripts.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] It has been used to detect errors in the mRNA predictions for a handful of genes.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] AlphaFold has shown certain limitations.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] AlphaFold has been used to predict structures of proteins of SARS-CoV-2, the causative agent of COVID-19.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] The structures of these proteins were pending experimental detection in early 2020.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] Results were reviewed by scientists at the Francis Crick Institute in the United Kingdom before being released to the broader research community.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] The team also confirmed accurate prediction against the experimentally determined SARS-CoV-2 spike protein that was shared in the Protein Data Bank, an international open-access database, before releasing the computationally determined structures of the under-studied protein molecules.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] The team acknowledged that although these protein structures might not be the subject of ongoing therapeutical research efforts, they will add to the community's understanding of the SARS-CoV-2 virus.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] Specifically, AlphaFold 2's prediction of the structure of the *ORF3a* protein was very similar to the structure determined by researchers at University of California, Berkeley using cryo-electron microscopy.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] This specific protein is believed to assist the virus in breaking out of the host cell once it replicates.
[src:protein-folding/alphafold] This protein is also believed to play a role in triggering the inflammatory response to the infection.
[src:protein-folding/anfinsen-s-dogma] Some proteins need the assistance of chaperone proteins to fold properly.
[src:protein-folding/anfinsen-s-dogma] It has been suggested that this disproves Anfinsen's dogma.
[src:protein-folding/anfinsen-s-dogma] However, the chaperones do not appear to affect the final state of the protein; they seem to work primarily by preventing aggregation of several protein molecules prior to the final folded state of the protein.
[src:protein-folding/anfinsen-s-dogma] However, at least some chaperones are required for the proper folding of their subject proteins.
[src:protein-folding/anfinsen-s-dogma] Many proteins can also undergo aggregation and misfolding.
[src:protein-folding/anfinsen-s-dogma] For example, prions are stable conformations of proteins which differ from the native folding state.
[src:protein-folding/anfinsen-s-dogma] In bovine spongiform encephalopathy, native proteins re-fold into a different stable conformation, which causes fatal amyloid buildup.
[src:protein-folding/anfinsen-s-dogma] Other amyloid diseases, including Alzheimer's disease and Parkinson's disease, are also exceptions to Anfinsen's dogma.
[src:protein-folding/anfinsen-s-dogma] Some proteins have multiple native structures, and change their fold based on some external factors.
[src:protein-folding/anfinsen-s-dogma] For example, the KaiB protein complex switches fold throughout the day, acting as a clock for cyanobacteria.
[src:protein-folding/anfinsen-s-dogma] It has been estimated that around 0.5–4% of Protein Data Bank (PDB) proteins switch folds.
[src:protein-folding/anfinsen-s-dogma] The switching between alternative structures is driven by interactions of the protein with small ligands or other proteins, by chemical modifications (such as phosphorylation) or by changed environmental conditions, such as temperature, pH or membrane potential.
[src:protein-folding/anfinsen-s-dogma] Each alternative structure may either correspond to the global minimum of free energy of the protein at the given conditions or be kinetically trapped in a higher local minimum of free energy.
[src:protein-folding/levinthal-s-paradox] In 1969, Cyrus Levinthal noted that, because of the many degrees of freedom in an unfolded polypeptide chain, the molecule has an astronomical number of possible conformations.
[src:protein-folding/levinthal-s-paradox] An estimate of 10300 was made in one of his papers (often incorrectly cited as the 1968 paper).
[src:protein-folding/levinthal-s-paradox] For example, a polypeptide of 100 residues will have 200 different phi and psi bond angles, two for each residue.
[src:protein-folding/levinthal-s-paradox] If each torsion angle can be in one of three stable conformations, the protein may adopt a maximum of 3200 different conformations, without even considering interactions between residues or the conformations of side-chains.
[src:protein-folding/levinthal-s-paradox] Therefore, if a protein were to reach its correctly folded configuration by sequentially sampling all possible conformations, it would need more time than the age of the universe to find its native conformation.
[src:protein-folding/levinthal-s-paradox] This remains true even if conformations are sampled at rapid nanosecond or picosecond rates.
[src:protein-folding/levinthal-s-paradox] The "paradox" is that most small proteins fold spontaneously on a millisecond or even microsecond time scale.
[src:protein-folding/levinthal-s-paradox] Insights into this paradox have been advanced by computational approaches to protein structure prediction.
[src:protein-folding/levinthal-s-paradox] Levinthal himself was aware that proteins fold spontaneously and on short timescales.
[src:protein-folding/levinthal-s-paradox] Indeed, the protein folding intermediates and the partially folded transition states were experimentally detected, which explains the fast protein folding.
[src:protein-folding/levinthal-s-paradox] Protein folding can be understood as a multidimensional optimization problem within a funnel-like energy landscape.
[src:protein-folding/levinthal-s-paradox] Any particular configuration of amino acids has a corresponding stability, and the protein will spontaneously follow its energetic gradient toward higher stability states.
[src:protein-folding/levinthal-s-paradox] This tendency directs the process of folding and dramatically shrinks the space of feasible structures the protein might adopt.
[src:protein-folding/levinthal-s-paradox] The protein traverses this landscape of energetic states to its native state, found at the bottom of the funnel.
[src:protein-folding/levinthal-s-paradox] This was shown by Christian Anfinsen in his famous experiments with ribonuclease A, demonstrating that an unfolded protein can refold to its native, functional structure, even in the absence of cellular machinery.
[src:protein-folding/levinthal-s-paradox] This validated Anfinsen's thermodynamic hypothesis, also known as Anfinsen's dogma, which states that the native structure of a protein is the state in which it has a minimum of free energy.
[src:protein-folding/levinthal-s-paradox] In the process of folding it is possible for proteins to become trapped in intermediate states, a locally optimal state, but not a globally optimal state.
[src:protein-folding/levinthal-s-paradox] This problem is addressed in part by chaperones, proteins which assist in the folding process, which help in bringing unfolded intermediates to their native state.
[src:protein-folding/levinthal-s-paradox] However, protein folding does not simply begin with a fully synthesized, unfolded peptide chain.
[src:protein-folding/levinthal-s-paradox] In cellular systems, folding commonly begins while the protein is being produced in the ribosome.
[src:protein-folding/levinthal-s-paradox] As each amino acid is added to the chain, residues can adopt secondary and tertiary structures, a process known as cotranslational folding.
[src:protein-folding/levinthal-s-paradox] According to Edward Trifonov and Igor Berezovsky, proteins fold by subunits (modules) of the size of 25–30 amino acids.
[src:protein-folding/levinthal-s-paradox] The problem of protein folding is increasingly being answered by computational methods.
[src:protein-folding/levinthal-s-paradox] Some computational approaches to protein structure prediction have sought to identify and simulate the mechanism of protein folding.
[src:protein-folding/levinthal-s-paradox] The development of tools such as AlphaFold leverage machine learning and the known structures of homologous proteins to predict unknown structures with high accuracy.
[src:protein-folding/levinthal-s-paradox] Levinthal's paradox was cited on the first page of the Scientific Background to the 2024 Nobel Prize in Chemistry (awarded to David Baker, Demis Hassabis, and John M.
[src:protein-folding/levinthal-s-paradox] Jumper for computational protein design and protein structure prediction) by way of demonstrating the sheer scale of the problem given the astronomical number of permutations.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The folding of many proteins begins even during the translation of the polypeptide chain.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The amino acids interact with each other to produce a well-defined three-dimensional structure, known as the protein's native state.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] This structure is determined by the amino-acid sequence or primary structure.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The correct three-dimensional structure is essential to function, although some parts of functional proteins may remain unfolded, indicating that protein dynamics are important.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Failure to fold into a native structure generally produces inactive proteins, but in some instances, misfolded proteins have modified or toxic functionality.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Several neurodegenerative and other diseases are believed to result from the accumulation of amyloid fibrils formed by misfolded proteins, the infectious varieties of which are known as prions.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Many allergies are caused by the incorrect folding of some proteins because the immune system does not produce the antibodies for certain protein structures.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Denaturation of proteins is a process of transition from a folded to an unfolded state.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] It happens in cooking, burns, proteinopathies, and other contexts.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Residual structure present, if any, in the supposedly unfolded state may form a folding initiation site and guide the subsequent folding reactions.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The duration of the folding process varies dramatically depending on the protein of interest.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] When studied outside the cell, the slowest folding proteins require many minutes or hours to fold, primarily due to proline isomerization, and must pass through a number of intermediate states, like checkpoints, before the process is complete.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] On the other hand, very small single-domain proteins with lengths of up to a hundred amino acids typically fold in a single step.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Time scales of milliseconds are the norm, and the fastest known protein folding reactions are complete within a few microseconds.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The folding time scale of a protein depends on its size, contact order, and circuit topology.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Understanding and simulating the protein folding process has been an important challenge for computational biology since the late 1960s.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The primary structure of a protein, its linear amino-acid sequence, determines its native conformation.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The specific amino acid residues and their position in the polypeptide chain are the determining factors for which portions of the protein fold closely together and form its three-dimensional conformation.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The amino acid composition is not as important as the sequence.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The essential fact of folding, however, remains that the amino acid sequence of each protein contains the information that specifies both the native structure and the pathway to attain that state.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] This is not to say that nearly identical amino acid sequences always fold similarly.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Conformations differ based on environmental factors as well; similar proteins fold differently based on where they are found.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Formation of a secondary structure is the first step in the folding process that a protein takes to assume its native structure.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Characteristic of secondary structure are the structures known as alpha helices and beta sheets that fold rapidly because they are stabilized by intramolecular hydrogen bonds, as was first characterized by Linus Pauling.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Formation of intramolecular hydrogen bonds provides another important contribution to protein stability. α-helices are formed by hydrogen bonding of the backbone to form a spiral shape (refer to figure on the right).
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The β pleated sheet is a structure that forms with the backbone bending over itself to form the hydrogen bonds (as displayed in the figure to the left).
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The hydrogen bonds are between the amide hydrogen and carbonyl oxygen of the peptide bond.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] There exists anti-parallel β pleated sheets and parallel β pleated sheets where the stability of the hydrogen bonds is stronger in the anti-parallel β sheet as it hydrogen bonds with the ideal 180 degree angle compared to the slanted hydrogen bonds formed by parallel sheets.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The α-Helices and β-Sheets are commonly amphipathic, meaning they have a hydrophilic and a hydrophobic portion.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] This ability helps in forming tertiary structure of a protein in which folding occurs so that the hydrophilic sides are facing the aqueous environment surrounding the protein and the hydrophobic sides are facing the hydrophobic core of the protein.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Secondary structure hierarchically gives way to tertiary structure formation.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Once the protein's tertiary structure is formed and stabilized by the hydrophobic interactions, there may also be covalent bonding in the form of disulfide bridges formed between two cysteine residues.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] These non-covalent and covalent contacts take a specific topological arrangement in a native structure of a protein.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Tertiary structure of a protein involves a single polypeptide chain; however, additional interactions of folded polypeptide chains give rise to quaternary structure formation.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Tertiary structure may give way to the formation of quaternary structure in some proteins, which usually involves the "assembly" or "coassembly" of subunits that have already folded; in other words, multiple polypeptide chains could interact to form a fully functional quaternary protein.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Folding is a spontaneous process that is mainly guided by hydrophobic interactions, formation of intramolecular hydrogen bonds, van der Waals forces, and it is opposed by conformational entropy.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The folding time scale of an isolated protein depends on its size, contact order, and circuit topology.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Inside cells, the process of folding often begins co-translationally, so that the N-terminus of the protein begins to fold while the C-terminal portion of the protein is still being synthesized by the ribosome; however, a protein molecule may fold spontaneously during or after biosynthesis.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] While these macromolecules may be regarded as "folding themselves", the process also depends on the solvent (water or lipid bilayer), the concentration of salts, the pH, the temperature, the possible presence of cofactors and of molecular chaperones.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Proteins will have limitations on their folding abilities by the restricted bending angles or conformations that are possible.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] These allowable angles of protein folding are described with a two-dimensional plot known as the Ramachandran plot, depicted with psi and phi angles of allowable rotation.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Protein folding must be thermodynamically favorable within a cell in order for it to be a spontaneous reaction.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Since it is known that protein folding is a spontaneous reaction, then it must assume a negative Gibbs free energy value.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Gibbs free energy in protein folding is directly related to enthalpy and entropy.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] For a negative delta G to arise and for protein folding to become thermodynamically favorable, then either enthalpy, entropy, or both terms must be favorable.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Minimizing the number of hydrophobic side-chains exposed to water is an important driving force behind the folding process.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The hydrophobic effect is the phenomenon in which the hydrophobic chains of a protein collapse into the core of the protein (away from the hydrophilic environment).
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] In an aqueous environment, the water molecules tend to aggregate around the hydrophobic regions or side chains of the protein, creating water shells of ordered water molecules.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] An ordering of water molecules around a hydrophobic region increases order in a system and therefore contributes a negative change in entropy (less entropy in the system).
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The water molecules are fixed in these water cages which drives the hydrophobic collapse, or the inward folding of the hydrophobic groups.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The hydrophobic collapse introduces entropy back to the system via the breaking of the water cages which frees the ordered water molecules.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The multitude of hydrophobic groups interacting within the core of the globular folded protein contributes a significant amount to protein stability after folding, because of the vastly accumulated van der Waals forces (specifically London Dispersion forces).
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The hydrophobic effect exists as a driving force in thermodynamics only if there is the presence of an aqueous medium with an amphiphilic molecule containing a large hydrophobic region.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The strength of hydrogen bonds depends on their environment; thus, H-bonds enveloped in a hydrophobic core contribute more than H-bonds exposed to the aqueous environment to the stability of the native state.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] In proteins with globular folds, hydrophobic amino acids tend to be interspersed along the primary sequence, rather than randomly distributed or clustered together.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] However, proteins that have recently been born de novo, which tend to be intrinsically disordered, show the opposite pattern of hydrophobic amino acid clustering along the primary sequence.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Molecular chaperones are a class of proteins that aid in the correct folding of other proteins *in vivo*.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Chaperones exist in all cellular compartments and interact with the polypeptide chain in order to allow the native three-dimensional conformation of the protein to form; however, chaperones themselves are not included in the final structure of the protein they are assisting in.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Chaperones may assist in folding even when the nascent polypeptide is being synthesized by the ribosome.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Chaperones are not to be confused with folding catalyst proteins, which catalyze chemical reactions responsible for slow steps in folding pathways.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Examples of folding catalysts are protein disulfide isomerases and peptidyl-prolyl isomerases that may be involved in formation of disulfide bonds or interconversion between cis and trans stereoisomers of peptide group.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Chaperones are shown to be critical in the process of protein folding *in vivo* because they provide the protein with the aid needed to assume its proper alignments and conformations efficiently enough to become "biologically relevant".
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] A fully denatured protein lacks both tertiary and secondary structure, and exists as a so-called random coil.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Under certain conditions some proteins can refold; however, in many cases, denaturation is irreversible.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Cells sometimes protect their proteins against the denaturing influence of heat with enzymes known as heat shock proteins (a type of chaperone), which assist other proteins both in folding and in remaining folded.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Heat shock proteins have been found in all species examined, from bacteria to humans, suggesting that they evolved very early and have an important function.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Some proteins never fold in cells at all except with the assistance of chaperones which either isolate individual proteins so that their folding is not interrupted by interactions with other proteins or help to unfold misfolded proteins, allowing them to refold into the correct native structure.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] This function is crucial to prevent the risk of precipitation into insoluble amorphous aggregates.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The external factors involved in protein denaturation or disruption of the native state include temperature, external fields (electric, magnetic), molecular crowding, and even the limitation of space (i.e. confinement), which can have a big influence on the folding of proteins.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] High concentrations of solutes, extremes of pH, mechanical forces, and the presence of chemical denaturants can contribute to protein denaturation, as well.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] These individual factors are categorized together as stresses.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Chaperones are shown to exist in increasing concentrations during times of cellular stress and help the proper folding of emerging proteins as well as denatured or misfolded ones.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Under some conditions proteins will not fold into their biochemically functional forms.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Temperatures above or below the range that cells tend to live in will cause thermally unstable proteins to unfold or denature (this is why boiling makes an egg white turn opaque).
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Protein thermal stability is far from constant, however; for example, hyperthermophilic archaea have been found that grow at temperatures as high as 122 °C, which of course requires that their full complement of vital proteins and protein assemblies be stable at that temperature or above.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The bacterium *E. coli* is the host for bacteriophage T4, and the phage encoded gp31 protein (P17313) appears to be structurally and functionally homologous to *E. coli* chaperone protein GroES and able to substitute for it in the assembly of bacteriophage T4 virus particles during infection.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Like GroES, gp31 forms a stable complex with GroEL chaperonin that is absolutely necessary for the folding and assembly in vivo of the bacteriophage T4 major capsid protein gp23.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] For example, the KaiB protein switches fold throughout the day, acting as a clock for cyanobacteria.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] It has been estimated that around 0.5–4% of PDB (Protein Data Bank) proteins switch folds.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] A protein is considered to be misfolded if it cannot achieve its normal native state.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] This can be due to mutations in the amino acid sequence or to a disruption of the normal folding process by external factors.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The misfolded protein typically contains beta sheets (β-sheets) that are organized in a supramolecular arrangement known as a cross-β structure.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] These β-sheet-rich assemblies are very stable, very insoluble, and generally resistant to proteolysis.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The structural stability of these fibrillar assemblies is caused by extensive interactions between the protein monomers, formed by backbone hydrogen bonds between their β-strands.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The misfolding of proteins can trigger the further misfolding and accumulation of other proteins into aggregates or oligomers.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The increased levels of aggregated proteins in the cell leads to formation of amyloid-like structures which can cause neurodegenerative disorders and cell death.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The amyloids are fibrillary structures that contain intermolecular hydrogen bonds which are highly insoluble and made from converted protein aggregates.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Therefore, the proteasome pathway may not be efficient enough to degrade the misfolded proteins prior to aggregation.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Misfolded proteins can interact with one another and form structured aggregates and gain toxicity through intermolecular interactions.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] These age onset degenerative diseases are associated with the aggregation of misfolded proteins into insoluble, extracellular aggregates and/or intracellular inclusions including cross-β amyloid fibrils.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] It is not completely clear whether the aggregates are the cause or merely a reflection of the loss of protein homeostasis, the balance between synthesis, folding, aggregation and protein turnover.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Recently the European Medicines Agency approved the use of Tafamidis or Vyndaqel (a kinetic stabilizer of tetrameric transthyretin) for the treatment of transthyretin amyloid diseases.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] This suggests that the process of amyloid fibril formation (and not the fibrils themselves) causes the degeneration of post-mitotic tissue in human amyloid diseases.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Misfolding and excessive degradation instead of folding and function leads to a number of proteinopathies, diseases such as antitrypsin-associated emphysema, cystic fibrosis and the lysosomal storage diseases, where loss of function is the origin of the disorder.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] While protein replacement therapy has historically been used to correct the latter disorders, an emerging approach is to use pharmaceutical chaperones to fold mutated proteins to render them functional.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] While inferences about protein folding can be made through mutation studies, typically, experimental techniques for studying protein folding rely on the gradual unfolding or folding of proteins and observing conformational changes using standard non-crystallographic techniques.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] X-ray crystallography is one of the more efficient and important methods for attempting to decipher the three dimensional configuration of a folded protein.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] To be able to conduct X-ray crystallography, the protein under investigation must be located inside a crystal lattice.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] To place a protein inside a crystal lattice, one must have a suitable solvent for crystallization, obtain a pure protein at supersaturated levels in solution, and precipitate the crystals in solution.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Once a protein is crystallized, X-ray beams can be concentrated through the crystal lattice which would diffract the beams or shoot them outwards in various directions.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] These exiting beams are correlated to the specific three-dimensional configuration of the protein enclosed within.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The X-rays specifically interact with the electron clouds surrounding the individual atoms within the protein crystal lattice and produce a discernible diffraction pattern.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Only by relating the electron density clouds with the amplitude of the X-rays can this pattern be read and lead to assumptions of the phases or phase angles involved that complicate this method.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Without the relation established through a mathematical basis known as Fourier transform, the "phase problem" would render predicting the diffraction patterns very difficult.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Emerging methods like multiple isomorphous replacement use the presence of a heavy metal ion to diffract the X-rays into a more predictable manner, reducing the number of variables involved and resolving the phase problem.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Fluorescence spectroscopy is a highly sensitive method for studying the folding state of proteins.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Three amino acids, phenylalanine (Phe), tyrosine (Tyr) and tryptophan (Trp), have intrinsic fluorescence properties, but only Tyr and Trp are used experimentally because their quantum yields are high enough to give good fluorescence signals.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Both Trp and Tyr are excited by a wavelength of 280 nm, whereas only Trp is excited by a wavelength of 295 nm.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Because of their aromatic character, Trp and Tyr residues are often found fully or partially buried in the hydrophobic core of proteins, at the interface between two protein domains, or at the interface between subunits of oligomeric proteins.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] In this apolar environment, they have high quantum yields and therefore high fluorescence intensities.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Upon disruption of the protein's tertiary or quaternary structure, these side chains become more exposed to the hydrophilic environment of the solvent, and their quantum yields decrease, leading to low fluorescence intensities.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] For Trp residues, the wavelength of their maximal fluorescence emission also depend on their environment.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Fluorescence spectroscopy can be used to characterize the equilibrium unfolding of proteins by measuring the variation in the intensity of fluorescence emission or in the wavelength of maximal emission as functions of a denaturant value.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The denaturant can be a chemical molecule (urea, guanidinium hydrochloride), temperature, pH, pressure, etc.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The equilibrium between the different but discrete protein states, i.e. native state, intermediate states, unfolded state, depends on the denaturant value; therefore, the global fluorescence signal of their equilibrium mixture also depends on this value.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] One thus obtains a profile relating the global protein signal to the denaturant value.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The profile of equilibrium unfolding may enable one to detect and identify intermediates of unfolding.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] General equations have been developed by Hugues Bedouelle to obtain the thermodynamic parameters that characterize the unfolding equilibria for homomeric or heteromeric proteins, up to trimers and potentially tetramers, from such profiles.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Fluorescence spectroscopy can be combined with fast-mixing devices such as stopped flow, to measure protein folding kinetics, generate a chevron plot and derive a Phi value analysis.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Circular dichroism is one of the most general and basic tools to study protein folding.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Circular dichroism spectroscopy measures the absorption of circularly polarized light.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] In proteins, structures such as alpha helices and beta sheets are chiral, and thus absorb such light.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The absorption of this light acts as a marker of the degree of foldedness of the protein ensemble.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] This technique has been used to measure equilibrium unfolding of the protein by measuring the change in this absorption as a function of denaturant concentration or temperature.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] A denaturant melt measures the free energy of unfolding as well as the protein's m value, or denaturant dependence.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] A temperature melt measures the denaturation temperature (Tm) of the protein.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] As for fluorescence spectroscopy, circular-dichroism spectroscopy can be combined with fast-mixing devices such as stopped flow to measure protein folding kinetics and to generate chevron plots.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The more recent developments of vibrational circular dichroism (VCD) techniques for proteins, currently involving Fourier transform (FT) instruments, provide powerful means for determining protein conformations in solution even for very large protein molecules.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Such VCD studies of proteins can be combined with X-ray diffraction data for protein crystals, FT-IR data for protein solutions in heavy water (D2O), or quantum computations.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Protein nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) is able to collect protein structural data by inducing a magnet field through samples of concentrated protein.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] In NMR, depending on the chemical environment, certain nuclei will absorb specific radio-frequencies.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Because protein structural changes operate on a time scale from ns to ms, NMR is especially equipped to study intermediate structures in timescales of ps to s.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Some of the main techniques for studying proteins structure and non-folding protein structural changes include COSY, TOCSY, HSQC, time relaxation (T1 & T2), and NOE.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] NOE is especially useful because magnetization transfers can be observed between spatially proximal hydrogens are observed.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Different NMR experiments have varying degrees of timescale sensitivity that are appropriate for different protein structural changes.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] NOE can pick up bond vibrations or side chain rotations, however, NOE is too sensitive to pick up protein folding because it occurs at larger timescale.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Because protein folding takes place in about 50 to 3000 s−1 CPMG Relaxation dispersion and chemical exchange saturation transfer have become some of the primary techniques for NMR analysis of folding.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] In addition, both techniques are used to uncover excited intermediate states in the protein folding landscape.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] To do this, CPMG Relaxation dispersion takes advantage of the spin echo phenomenon.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] This technique exposes the target nuclei to a 90 pulse followed by one or more 180 pulses.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] As the nuclei refocus, a broad distribution indicates the target nuclei is involved in an intermediate excited state.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] By looking at Relaxation dispersion plots the data collect information on the thermodynamics and kinetics between the excited and ground.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Saturation Transfer measures changes in signal from the ground state as excited states become perturbed.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] It uses weak radio frequency irradiation to saturate the excited state of a particular nuclei which transfers its saturation to the ground state.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] This signal is amplified by decreasing the magnetization (and the signal) of the ground state.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The main limitations in NMR is that its resolution decreases with proteins that are larger than 25 kDa and is not as detailed as X-ray crystallography.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Additionally, protein NMR analysis is quite difficult and can propose multiple solutions from the same NMR spectrum.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] In a study focused on the folding of an amyotrophic lateral sclerosis involved protein SOD1, excited intermediates were studied with relaxation dispersion and Saturation transfer.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] SOD1 had been previously tied to many disease causing mutants which were assumed to be involved in protein aggregation, however the mechanism was still unknown.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] By using Relaxation Dispersion and Saturation Transfer experiments many excited intermediate states were uncovered misfolding in the SOD1 mutants.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Dual polarisation interferometry is a surface-based technique for measuring the optical properties of molecular layers.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Similar to circular dichroism, the stimulus for folding can be a denaturant or temperature.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The study of protein folding has been greatly advanced in recent years by the development of fast, time-resolved techniques.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Experimenters rapidly trigger the folding of a sample of unfolded protein and observe the resulting dynamics.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Fast techniques in use include ultrafast mixing of solutions, photochemical methods, and laser temperature jump spectroscopy.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Among the many scientists who have contributed to the development of these techniques are Heinrich Roder, Terry Oas, Harry Gray, Martin Gruebele, Brian Dyer, William Eaton, Sheena Radford, Chris Dobson, Alan Fersht, Bengt Nölting and Lars Konermann.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Proteolysis is routinely used to probe the fraction unfolded under a wide range of solution conditions (e.g. fast parallel proteolysis (FASTpp).
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Single molecule techniques such as optical tweezers and AFM have been used to understand protein folding mechanisms of isolated proteins as well as proteins with chaperones.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Optical tweezers have been used to stretch single protein molecules from their C- and N-termini and unfold them to allow study of the subsequent refolding.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] It was discovered – using single molecule optical tweezers measurement – that calcium-bound vWF acts as a shear force sensor in the blood.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Shear force leads to unfolding of the A2 domain of vWF, whose refolding rate is dramatically enhanced in the presence of calcium.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] It has also been shown that the simple src SH3 domain accesses multiple unfolding pathways under force.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Biotin painting enables condition-specific cellular snapshots of (un)folded proteins.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Biotin 'painting' shows a bias towards predicted Intrinsically disordered proteins.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Computational studies of protein folding includes three main aspects related to the prediction of protein stability, kinetics, and structure.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] A 2013 review summarizes the available computational methods for protein folding.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] In 1969, Cyrus Levinthal noted that, because of the very large number of degrees of freedom in an unfolded polypeptide chain, the molecule has an astronomical number of possible conformations.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] An estimate of 3300 or 10143 was made in one of his papers.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Based upon the observation that proteins fold much faster than this, Levinthal then proposed that a random conformational search does not occur, and the protein must, therefore, fold through a series of meta-stable intermediate states.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The configuration space of a protein during folding can be visualized as an energy landscape.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] In addition, the acquisition of the folded state had to become a sufficiently fast process.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Even though nature has reduced the level of *frustration* in proteins, some degree of it remains up to now as can be observed in the presence of local minima in the energy landscape of proteins.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] A consequence of these evolutionarily selected sequences is that proteins are generally thought to have globally "funneled energy landscapes" (a term coined by José Onuchic) that are largely directed toward the native state.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] This "folding funnel" landscape allows the protein to fold to the native state through any of a large number of pathways and intermediates, rather than being restricted to a single mechanism.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The theory is supported by both computational simulations of model proteins and experimental studies, and it has been used to improve methods for protein structure prediction and design.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The description of protein folding by the leveling free-energy landscape is also consistent with the 2nd law of thermodynamics.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Physically, thinking of landscapes in terms of visualizable potential or total energy surfaces simply with maxima, saddle points, minima, and funnels, rather like geographic landscapes, is perhaps a little misleading.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The relevant description is really a high-dimensional phase space in which manifolds might take a variety of more complicated topological forms.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The unfolded polypeptide chain begins at the top of the funnel where it may assume the largest number of unfolded variations and is in its highest energy state.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Energy landscapes such as these indicate that there are a large number of initial possibilities, but only a single native state is possible; however, it does not reveal the numerous folding pathways that are possible.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] A different molecule of the same exact protein may be able to follow marginally different folding pathways, seeking different lower energy intermediates, as long as the same native structure is reached.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Different pathways may have different frequencies of utilization depending on the thermodynamic favorability of each pathway.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] This means that if one pathway is found to be more thermodynamically favorable than another, it is likely to be used more frequently in the pursuit of the native structure.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] As the protein begins to fold and assume its various conformations, it always seeks a more thermodynamically favorable structure than before and thus continues through the energy funnel.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Formation of secondary structures is a strong indication of increased stability within the protein, and only one combination of secondary structures assumed by the polypeptide backbone will have the lowest energy and therefore be present in the native state of the protein.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Among the first structures to form once the polypeptide begins to fold are alpha helices and beta turns, where alpha helices can form in as little as 100 nanoseconds and beta turns in 1 microsecond.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] There exists a saddle point in the energy funnel landscape where the transition state for a particular protein is found.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The transition state in the energy funnel diagram is the conformation that must be assumed by every molecule of that protein if the protein wishes to finally assume the native structure.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] No protein may assume the native structure without first passing through the transition state.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The transition state can be referred to as a variant or premature form of the native state rather than just another intermediary step.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The folding of the transition state is shown to be rate-determining, and even though it exists in a higher energy state than the native fold, it greatly resembles the native structure.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Within the transition state, there exists a nucleus around which the protein is able to fold, formed by a process referred to as "nucleation condensation" where the structure begins to collapse onto the nucleus.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Several large-scale computational projects, such as Rosetta@home, Folding@home and Foldit, target protein folding.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Long continuous-trajectory simulations have been performed on Anton, a massively parallel supercomputer designed and built around custom ASICs and interconnects by D.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The longest published result of a simulation performed using Anton as of 2011 was a 2.936 millisecond simulation of NTL9 at 355 K.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Such simulations are currently able to unfold and refold small proteins (<150 amino acids residues) in equilibrium and predict how mutations affect folding kinetics and stability.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] In 2020 a team of researchers that used AlphaFold, an artificial intelligence (AI) protein structure prediction program developed by DeepMind placed first in CASP, a long-standing structure prediction contest.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] The team achieved a level of accuracy much higher than any other group.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] It scored above 90% for around two-thirds of the proteins in CASP's global distance test (GDT), a test that measures the degree of similarity between the structure predicted by a computational program, and the empirical structure determined experimentally in a lab.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] A score of 100 is considered a complete match, within the distance cutoff used for calculating GDT.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] AlphaFold's protein structure prediction results at CASP were described as "transformational" and "astounding".
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Some researchers noted that the accuracy is not high enough for a third of its predictions, and that it does not reveal the physical mechanism of protein folding for the protein folding problem to be considered solved.
[src:protein-folding/protein-folding] Nevertheless, it is considered a significant achievement in computational biology and great progress towards a decades-old grand challenge of biology, predicting the structure of proteins.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] Secondary structure is formally defined by the pattern of hydrogen bonds between the amino hydrogen and carboxyl oxygen atoms in the peptide backbone.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] Secondary structure may alternatively be defined based on the regular pattern of backbone dihedral angles in a particular region of the Ramachandran plot regardless of whether it has the correct hydrogen bonds.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] The concept of secondary structure was introduced by Kaj Ulrik Linderstrøm-Lang at Stanford in 1952.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] Other types of biopolymers such as nucleic acids also possess characteristic secondary structures.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] The most common secondary structures are alpha helices and beta sheets.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] Other helices, such as the 310 helix and π helix, are calculated to have energetically favorable hydrogen-bonding patterns but are rarely observed in natural proteins except at the ends of α helices due to unfavorable backbone packing in the center of the helix.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] Other extended structures such as the polyproline helix and alpha sheet are rare in native state proteins but are often hypothesized as important protein folding intermediates.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] Tight turns and loose, flexible loops link the more "regular" secondary structure elements.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] The random coil is not a true secondary structure, but is the class of conformations that indicate an absence of regular secondary structure.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] Amino acids vary in their ability to form the various secondary structure elements.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] Turns and bends are preferred by glycine (G), asparagine (N), proline (P), aspartate (D) and serine (S), whereas the last two amino acids, cysteine (C) and histidine (H) show no preference.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] Besides this, proline and glycine are sometimes known as "helix breakers" because they disrupt the regularity of the α helical backbone conformation; However, these preferences are not strong enough to produce a reliable method of predicting secondary structure from sequence alone.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] Low frequency collective vibrations are thought to be sensitive to local rigidity within proteins, revealing beta structures to be generically more rigid than alpha or disordered proteins.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] Neutron scattering measurements have directly connected the spectral feature at ~1 THz to collective motions of the secondary structure of beta-barrel protein GFP.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] Hydrogen bonding patterns in secondary structures may be significantly distorted, which makes automatic determination of secondary structure difficult.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] There are several methods for formally defining protein secondary structure (e.g., DSSP, DEFINE, STRIDE, ScrewFit, SST).
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] The Dictionary of Protein Secondary Structure, in short DSSP, is commonly used to describe the protein secondary structure with single letter codes.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] The secondary structure is assigned based on hydrogen bonding patterns as those initially proposed by Pauling et al. in 1951 (before any protein structure had ever been experimentally determined).
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] 'Coil' is often codified as ' ' (space), C (coil) or '–' (dash).
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] The helices (G, H and I) and sheet conformations are all required to have a reasonable length.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] This means that 2 adjacent residues in the primary structure must form the same hydrogen bonding pattern.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] If the helix or sheet hydrogen bonding pattern is too short they are designated as T or B, respectively.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] Other protein secondary structure assignment categories exist (sharp turns, Omega loops, etc.), but they are less frequently used.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] Secondary structure is defined by hydrogen bonding, so the exact definition of a hydrogen bond is critical.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] The standard hydrogen-bond definition for secondary structure is that of DSSP, which is a purely electrostatic model.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] It assigns charges of ±*q*1 ≈ 0.42*e* to the carbonyl carbon and oxygen, respectively, and charges of ±*q*2 ≈ 0.20*e* to the amide hydrogen and nitrogen, respectively.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] According to DSSP, a hydrogen-bond exists if and only if *E* is less than −0.5 kcal/mol (−2.1 kJ/mol).
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] Although the DSSP formula is a relatively crude approximation of the *physical* hydrogen-bond energy, it is generally accepted as a tool for defining secondary structure.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] SST is a Bayesian method to assign secondary structure to protein coordinate data using the Shannon information criterion of Minimum Message Length (MML) inference.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] SST treats any assignment of secondary structure as a potential hypothesis that attempts to explain (compress) given protein coordinate data.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] The core idea is that the ***best*** secondary structural assignment is the one that can explain (compress) the coordinates of a given protein coordinates in the most economical way, thus linking the inference of secondary structure to lossless data compression.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] SST detects **π** and **310** helical caps to standard **α**-helices, and automatically assembles the various extended strands into consistent β-pleated sheets.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] It provides a readable output of dissected secondary structural elements, and a corresponding PyMol-loadable script to visualize the assigned secondary structural elements individually.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] The rough secondary-structure content of a biopolymer (e.g., "this protein is 40% α-helix and 20% β-sheet") can be estimated spectroscopically.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] For proteins, a common method is far-ultraviolet (far-UV, 170–250 nm) circular dichroism.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] A pronounced double minimum at 208 and 222 nm indicate α-helical structure, whereas a single minimum at 204 nm or 217 nm reflects random-coil or β-sheet structure, respectively.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] A less common method is infrared spectroscopy, which detects differences in the bond oscillations of amide groups due to hydrogen-bonding.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] Finally, secondary-structure contents may be estimated accurately using the chemical shifts of an initially unassigned NMR spectrum.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] Predicting protein tertiary structure from only its amino sequence is a very challenging problem (see protein structure prediction), but using the simpler secondary structure definitions is more tractable.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] Early methods of secondary-structure prediction were restricted to predicting the three predominate states: helix, sheet, or random coil.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] These methods were based on the helix- or sheet-forming propensities of individual amino acids, sometimes coupled with rules for estimating the free energy of forming secondary structure elements.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] The first widely used techniques to predict protein secondary structure from the amino acid sequence were the Chou–Fasman method and the GOR method.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] Although such methods claimed to achieve ~60% accurate in predicting which of the three states (helix/sheet/coil) a residue adopts, blind computing assessments later showed that the actual accuracy was much lower.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] For illustration, a given protein might have a glycine at a given position, which by itself might suggest a random coil there.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] However, multiple sequence alignment might reveal that helix-favoring amino acids occur at that position (and nearby positions) in 95% of homologous proteins spanning nearly a billion years of evolution.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] Moreover, by examining the average hydrophobicity at that and nearby positions, the same alignment might also suggest a pattern of residue solvent accessibility consistent with an α-helix.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] Taken together, these factors would suggest that the glycine of the original protein adopts α-helical structure, rather than random coil.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] Several types of methods are used to combine all the available data to form a 3-state prediction, including neural networks, hidden Markov models and support vector machines.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] Modern prediction methods also provide a confidence score for their predictions at every position.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] Secondary-structure prediction methods were evaluated by the Critical Assessment of protein Structure Prediction (CASP) experiments and continuously benchmarked, e.g. by EVA (benchmark).
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] Based on these tests, the most accurate methods were Psipred, SAM, PORTER, PROF, and SABLE.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] The chief area for improvement appears to be the prediction of β-strands; residues confidently predicted as β-strand are likely to be so, but the methods are apt to overlook some β-strand segments (false negatives).
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] There is likely an upper limit of ~90% prediction accuracy overall, due to the idiosyncrasies of the standard method (DSSP) for assigning secondary-structure classes (helix/strand/coil) to PDB structures, against which the predictions are benchmarked.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] Accurate secondary-structure prediction is a key element in the prediction of tertiary structure, in all but the simplest (homology modeling) cases.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] For example, a confidently predicted pattern of six secondary structure elements βαββαβ is the signature of a ferredoxin fold.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] Both protein and nucleic acid secondary structures can be used to aid in multiple sequence alignment.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] These alignments can be made more accurate by the inclusion of secondary structure information in addition to simple sequence information.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] This is sometimes less useful in RNA because base pairing is much more highly conserved than sequence.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] Distant relationships between proteins whose primary structures are unalignable can sometimes be found by secondary structure.
[src:protein-folding/protein-secondary-structure] It has been shown that α-helices are more stable, robust to mutations, and designable than β-strands in natural proteins, thus designing functional all-α proteins is likely to be easier that designing proteins with both helices and strands; this has been recently confirmed experimentally.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Protein structure prediction is one of the most important goals pursued by computational biology and addresses Levinthal's paradox.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Accurate structure prediction has important applications in medicine (for example, in drug design) and biotechnology (for example, in novel enzyme design).
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Starting in 1994, the performance of current methods is assessed biennially in the *Critical Assessment of Structure Prediction* (CASP) experiment.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] A continuous evaluation of protein structure prediction web servers is performed by the community project *Continuous Automated Model EvaluatiOn* (CAMEO3D).
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Proteins are chains of amino acids joined together by peptide bonds.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Many conformations of this chain are possible due to the rotation of the main chain about the two torsion angles φ and ψ at the Cα atom.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] This **conformational flexibility** is responsible for differences in the three-dimensional structure of proteins.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The peptide bonds in the chain are polar, i.e. they have separated positive and negative charges (partial charges) in the carbonyl group, which can act as hydrogen bond acceptor and in the NH group, which can act as hydrogen bond donor.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] These groups can therefore interact in the protein structure.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Proteins consist mostly of 20 different types of L-α-amino acids (the proteinogenic amino acids).
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] These can be classified according to the chemistry of the side chain, which also plays an important structural role.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Glycine takes on a special position, as it has the smallest side chain, only one hydrogen atom, and therefore can increase the local flexibility in the protein structure.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Cysteine in contrast can react with another cysteine residue to form one cystine and thereby form a cross link stabilizing the whole structure.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Protein structure arises from a sequence of secondary structure elements, such as α helices and β sheets.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] In secondary structures, regular patterns of H-bonds are formed between the main chain NH and CO groups of spatially neighboring amino acids, and the amino acids have similar Φ and ψ angles.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Formation of these secondary structures efficiently satisfies the hydrogen bonding capacities of the peptide bonds.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The secondary structures can be tightly packed in the protein core in a hydrophobic environment, but they can also be present at a polar protein surface.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Each amino acid side chain has a limited volume to occupy and a limited number of possible interactions with other nearby side chains, a situation that must be taken into account in molecular modeling and alignments.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The α-helix is the most abundant type of secondary structure in proteins.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The α-helix has 3.6 amino acids per turn with an H-bond formed between every fourth residue; the average length is 10 amino acids (3 turns) or 10 Å but varies from 5 to 40 (1.5 to 11 turns).
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The alignment of the H-bonds creates a dipole moment for the helix with a resulting partial positive charge at the amino end of the helix.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Because this region has free NH2 groups, it will interact with negatively charged groups such as phosphates.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The most common location of α-helices is at the surface of protein cores, where they provide an interface with the aqueous environment.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The inner-facing side of the helix tends to have hydrophobic amino acids and the outer-facing side hydrophilic amino acids.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Thus, every third of four amino acids along the chain will tend to be hydrophobic, a pattern that can be quite readily detected.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] In the leucine zipper motif, a repeating pattern of leucines on the facing sides of two adjacent helices is highly predictive of the motif.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] A helical-wheel plot can be used to show this repeated pattern.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Other α-helices buried in the protein core or in cellular membranes have a higher and more regular distribution of hydrophobic amino acids, and are highly predictive of such structures.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Helices exposed on the surface have a lower proportion of hydrophobic amino acids.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Amino acid content can be predictive of an α-helical region.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Regions richer in alanine (A), glutamic acid (E), leucine (L), and methionine (M) and poorer in proline (P), glycine (G), tyrosine (Y), and serine (S) tend to form an α-helix.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Proline destabilizes or breaks an α-helix but can be present in longer helices, forming a bend.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] β-sheets are formed by H-bonds between an average of 5–10 consecutive amino acids in one portion of the chain with another 5–10 farther down the chain.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The interacting regions may be adjacent, with a short loop in between, or far apart, with other structures in between.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Every chain may run in the same direction to form a parallel sheet, or in the reverse direction to form an antiparallel sheet, or the chains may form a mixed sheet.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The pattern of hydrogen bonding is different in the parallel and antiparallel configurations.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Each amino acid in the interior strands of the sheet forms two H-bonds with neighboring amino acids, whereas each amino acid on the outside strands forms only one bond with an interior strand.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Looking across the sheet at right angles to the strands, more distant strands are rotated slightly counterclockwise to form a left-handed twist.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The Cα-atoms alternate above and below the sheet in a pleated structure, and the R side groups of the amino acids alternate above and below the pleats.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The Φ and Ψ angles of the amino acids in sheets vary considerably in one region of the Ramachandran plot.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] It is more difficult to predict the location of β-sheets than of α-helices.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The situation improves somewhat when the amino acid variation in multiple sequence alignments is taken into account.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Parts of the protein may have fixed three-dimensional structure without regular structures.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] They should not be confused with disordered or unfolded segments of proteins or random coil, an unfolded polypeptide chain lacking any fixed three-dimensional structure.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] These parts are frequently called "deltas" (*Δ*) because they connect β-sheets and α-helices.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Deltas are usually located at protein surface, and therefore mutations of their residues are more easily tolerated.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Having more substitutions, insertions, and deletions in a certain region of a sequence alignment maybe an indication of some delta.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The positions of introns in genomic DNA may correlate with the locations of loops in the encoded protein .
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Deltas also tend to have charged and polar amino acids and are frequently a component of active sites.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Proteins may be classified according to both structural and sequential similarity.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] For structural classification, the sizes and spatial arrangements of secondary structures described in the above paragraph are compared in known three-dimensional structures.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Classification based on sequence similarity was historically the first to be used.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Initially, similarity based on alignments of whole sequences was performed.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Later, proteins were classified on the basis of the occurrence of conserved amino acid patterns.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Databases that classify proteins by one or more of these schemes are available.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] In considering protein classification schemes, it is important to keep several observations in mind.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] First, two entirely different protein sequences from different evolutionary origins may fold into a similar structure.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Conversely, the sequence of an ancient gene for a given structure may have diverged considerably in different species while at the same time maintaining the same basic structural features.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Recognizing any remaining sequence similarity in such cases may be a very difficult task.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Second, two proteins that share a significant degree of sequence similarity either with each other or with a third sequence also share an evolutionary origin and should share some structural features also.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] However, gene duplication and genetic rearrangements during evolution may give rise to new gene copies, which can then evolve into proteins with new function and structure.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The more commonly used terms for evolutionary and structural relationships among proteins are listed below.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Many additional terms are used for various kinds of structural features found in proteins.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Descriptions of such terms may be found at the CATH Web site, the Structural Classification of Proteins (SCOP) Web site, and a Glaxo Wellcome tutorial on the Swiss bioinformatics Expasy Web site.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] a localized combination of amino acid side groups within the tertiary (three-dimensional) or quaternary (protein subunit) structure that can interact with a chemically specific substrate and that provides the protein with biological activity.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Proteins of very different amino acid sequences may fold into a structure that produces the same active site.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] is the relative orientations of secondary structures in a three-dimensional structure without regard to whether or not they share a similar loop structure.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] a type of architecture that also has a conserved loop structure.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] is a conserved amino acid sequence pattern in a family of proteins.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The pattern includes a series of possible matches at each position in the represented sequences, but there are not any inserted or deleted positions in the pattern or in the sequences.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] By way of contrast, sequence profiles are a type of scoring matrix that represents a similar set of patterns that includes insertions and deletions.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] a term used to classify protein domains according to their secondary structural content and organization.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] were originally recognized by Levitt and Chothia (1976), and several others have been added in the SCOP database.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Three classes are given in the CATH database: mainly-α, mainly-β, and α–β, with the α–β class including both alternating α/β and α+β structures.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] the portion of a folded protein molecule that comprises the hydrophobic interior of α-helices and β-sheets.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The compact structure brings together side groups of amino acids into close enough proximity so that they can interact.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] When comparing protein structures, as in the SCOP database, core is the region common to most of the structures that share a common fold or that are in the same superfamily.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] In structure prediction, core is sometimes defined as the arrangement of secondary structures that is likely to be conserved during evolutionary change.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] a segment of a polypeptide chain that can fold into a three-dimensional structure irrespective of the presence of other segments of the chain.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The separate domains of a given protein may interact extensively or may be joined only by a length of polypeptide chain.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] A protein with several domains may use these domains for functional interactions with different molecules.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] a group of proteins of similar biochemical function that are more than 50% identical when aligned.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] A protein family comprises proteins with the same function in different organisms (orthologous sequences) but may also include proteins in the same organism (paralogous sequences) derived from gene duplication and rearrangements.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] If a multiple sequence alignment of a protein family reveals a common level of similarity throughout the lengths of the proteins, PIR refers to the family as a homeomorphic family.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The aligned region is referred to as a homeomorphic domain, and this region may comprise several smaller homology domains that are shared with other families.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Families may be further subdivided into subfamilies or grouped into superfamilies based on respective higher or lower levels of sequence similarity.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The SCOP database reports 1296 families and the CATH database (version 1.7 beta), reports 1846 families.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] When the sequences of proteins with the same function are examined in greater detail, some are found to share high sequence similarity.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] They are obviously members of the same family by the above criteria.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] However, others are found that have very little, or even insignificant, sequence similarity with other family members.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] In such cases, the family relationship between two distant family members A and C can often be demonstrated by finding an additional family member B that shares significant similarity with both A and C.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Thus, B provides a connecting link between A and C.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Another approach is to examine distant alignments for highly conserved matches.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] At a level of identity of 50%, proteins are likely to have the same three-dimensional structure, and the identical atoms in the sequence alignment will also superimpose within approximately 1 Å in the structural model.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Thus, if the structure of one member of a family is known, a reliable prediction may be made for a second member of the family, and the higher the identity level, the more reliable the prediction.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Protein structural modeling can be performed by examining how well the amino acid substitutions fit into the core of the three-dimensional structure.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] ) and the DALI/FSSP Web site, two structures that have a significant level of structural similarity but not necessarily significant sequence similarity.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] similar to structural motif, includes a larger combination of secondary structural units in the same configuration.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Thus, proteins sharing the same fold have the same combination of secondary structures that are connected by similar loops.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] An example is the Rossman fold comprising several alternating α helices and parallel β strands.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] In the SCOP, CATH, and FSSP databases, the known protein structures have been classified into hierarchical levels of structural complexity with the fold as a basic level of classification.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] an extended sequence pattern, generally found by sequence alignment methods, that indicates a common evolutionary origin among the aligned sequences.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] A homology domain is generally longer than motifs.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The domain may include all of a given protein sequence or only a portion of the sequence.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Some domains are complex and made up of several smaller homology domains that became joined to form a larger one during evolution.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] a region of conserved amino acid patterns comprising one or more motifs and considered to be a fundamental unit of structure or function.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The presence of a module has also been used to classify proteins into families.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] a conserved pattern of amino acids that is found in two or more proteins.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] catalog, a motif is an amino acid pattern that is found in a group of proteins that have a similar biochemical activity, and that often is near the active site of the protein.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Examples of sequence motif databases are the Prosite catalog and the Stanford Motifs Database.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] a combination of several secondary structural elements produced by the folding of adjacent sections of the polypeptide chain into a specific three-dimensional configuration.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] An example is the helix-loop-helix motif.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Structural motifs are also referred to as supersecondary structures and folds.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] represents a conserved region in a multiple sequence alignment with no gaps.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Each matrix column represents the variation found in one column of the multiple sequence alignment.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] represents the amino acid variation found in an alignment of proteins that fall into the same structural class.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Matrix columns represent the amino acid variation found at one amino acid position in the aligned structures.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] the linear amino acid sequence of a protein, which chemically is a polypeptide chain composed of amino acids joined by peptide bonds.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] a scoring matrix that represents a multiple sequence alignment of a protein family.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The profile is usually obtained from a well-conserved region in a multiple sequence alignment.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The profile is in the form of a matrix with each column representing a position in the alignment and each row one of the amino acids.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Matrix values give the likelihood of each amino acid at the corresponding position in the alignment.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The profile is moved along the target sequence to locate the best scoring regions by a dynamic programming algorithm.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Gaps are allowed during matching and a gap penalty is included in this case as a negative score when no amino acid is matched.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] a scoring matrix that represents which amino acids should fit well and which should fit poorly at sequential positions in a known protein structure.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Profile columns represent sequential positions in the structure, and profile rows represent the 20 amino acids.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] As with a sequence profile, the structural profile is moved along a target sequence to find the highest possible alignment score by a dynamic programming algorithm.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Gaps may be included and receive a penalty.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The resulting score provides an indication as to whether or not the target protein might adopt such a structure.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] the three-dimensional configuration of a protein molecule comprising several independent polypeptide chains.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] the interactions that occur between the C, O, and NH groups on amino acids in a polypeptide chain to form α-helices, β-sheets, turns, loops, and other forms, and that facilitate the folding into a three-dimensional structure.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] a group of protein families of the same or different lengths that are related by distant yet detectable sequence similarity.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Originally, Dayhoff defined the cutoff for superfamily status as being the chance that the sequences are not related of 10 6, on the basis of an alignment score (Dayhoff et al.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Proteins with few identities in an alignment of the sequences but with a convincingly common number of structural and functional features are placed in the same superfamily.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] At the level of three-dimensional structure, superfamily proteins will share common structural features such as a common fold, but there may also be differences in the number and arrangement of secondary structures.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] to refer to superfamilies that are composed of sequences that can be aligned from end to end, representing a sharing of single sequence homology domain, a region of similarity that extends throughout the alignment.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] This domain may also comprise smaller homology domains that are shared with other protein families and superfamilies.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Although a given protein sequence may contain domains found in several superfamilies, thus indicating a complex evolutionary history, sequences will be assigned to only one homeomorphic superfamily based on the presence of similarity throughout a multiple sequence alignment.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The superfamily alignment may also include regions that do not align either within or at the ends of the alignment.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] In contrast, sequences in the same family align well throughout the alignment.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] a term with similar meaning to a structural motif.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Tertiary structure is the three-dimensional or globular structure formed by the packing together or folding of secondary structures of a polypeptide chain.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The accuracy of current protein secondary structure prediction methods is assessed in weekly benchmarks such as LiveBench and EVA.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Early methods of secondary structure prediction, introduced in the 1960s and early 1970s, focused on identifying likely alpha helices and were based mainly on helix-coil transition models.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Significantly more accurate predictions that included beta sheets were introduced in the 1970s and relied on statistical assessments based on probability parameters derived from known solved structures.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] These methods, applied to a single sequence, are typically at most about 60–65% accurate, and often underpredict beta sheets.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Since the 1980s, artificial neural networks have been applied to the prediction of protein structures.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The evolutionary conservation of secondary structures can be exploited by simultaneously assessing many homologous sequences in a multiple sequence alignment, by calculating the net secondary structure propensity of an aligned column of amino acids.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] In concert with larger databases of known protein structures and modern machine learning methods such as neural nets and support vector machines, these methods can achieve up to 80% overall accuracy in globular proteins.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The theoretical upper limit of accuracy is around 90%, partly due to idiosyncrasies in DSSP assignment near the ends of secondary structures, where local conformations vary under native conditions but may be forced to assume a single conformation in crystals due to packing constraints.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Dramatic conformational changes related to the protein's function or environment can also alter local secondary structure.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] To date, over 20 different secondary structure prediction methods have been developed.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] One of the first algorithms was Chou–Fasman method, which relies predominantly on probability parameters determined from relative frequencies of each amino acid's appearance in each type of secondary structure.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The original Chou-Fasman parameters, determined from the small sample of structures solved in the mid-1970s, produce poor results compared to modern methods, though the parameterization has been updated since it was first published.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The Chou-Fasman method is roughly 50–60% accurate in predicting secondary structures.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The next notable program was the GOR method is an information theory-based method.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] It uses the more powerful probabilistic technique of Bayesian inference.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The approach is both more sensitive and more accurate than that of Chou and Fasman because amino acid structural propensities are only strong for a small number of amino acids such as proline and glycine.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Weak contributions from each of many neighbors can add up to strong effects overall.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The original GOR method was roughly 65% accurate and is dramatically more successful in predicting alpha helices than beta sheets, which it frequently mispredicted as loops or disorganized regions.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Another big step forward was using machine learning methods.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] First artificial neural networks methods were used.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] As a training sets they use solved structures to identify common sequence motifs associated with particular arrangements of secondary structures.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] PSIPRED and JPRED are some of the most known programs based on neural networks for protein secondary structure prediction.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Next, support vector machines have proven particularly useful for predicting the locations of turns, which are difficult to identify with statistical methods.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Extensions of machine learning techniques attempt to predict more fine-grained local properties of proteins, such as backbone dihedral angles in unassigned regions.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Both SVMs and neural networks have been applied to this problem.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] More recently, real-value torsion angles can be accurately predicted by SPINE-X and successfully employed for ab initio structure prediction.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] It is reported that in addition to the protein sequence, secondary structure formation depends on other factors.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] For example, it is reported that secondary structure tendencies depend also on local environment, solvent accessibility of residues, protein structural class, and even the organism from which the proteins are obtained.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Based on such observations, some studies have shown that secondary structure prediction can be improved by addition of information about protein structural class, residue accessible surface area and also contact number information.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The practical role of protein structure prediction is now more important than ever.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Massive amounts of protein sequence data are produced by modern large-scale DNA sequencing efforts such as the Human Genome Project.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Despite community-wide efforts in structural genomics, the output of experimentally determined protein structures—typically by time-consuming and relatively expensive X-ray crystallography or NMR spectroscopy—is lagging far behind the output of protein sequences.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The protein structure prediction remains an extremely difficult and unresolved undertaking.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The two main problems are the calculation of protein free energy and finding the global minimum of this energy.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] A protein structure prediction method must explore the space of possible protein structures which is astronomically large.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] These problems can be partially bypassed in "comparative" or homology modeling and fold recognition methods, in which the search space is pruned by the assumption that the protein in question adopts a structure that is close to the experimentally determined structure of another homologous protein.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] In contrast, the de novo protein structure prediction methods must explicitly resolve these problems.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The progress and challenges in protein structure prediction have been reviewed by Zhang.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Most tertiary structure modelling methods, such as Rosetta, are optimized for modelling the tertiary structure of single protein domains.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] A step called **domain parsing**, or **domain boundary prediction**, is usually done first to split a protein into potential structural domains.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] As with the rest of tertiary structure prediction, this can be done comparatively from known structures or *ab initio* with the sequence only (usually by machine learning, assisted by covariation).
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The structures for individual domains are docked together in a process called **domain assembly** to form the final tertiary structure.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] As of 2009, a 50-residue protein could be simulated atom-by-atom on a supercomputer for 1 millisecond.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] As of 2012, comparable stable-state sampling could be done on a standard desktop with a new graphics card and more sophisticated algorithms.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] A much larger simulation timescales can be achieved using coarse-grained modeling.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The assumption is when single residue mutations are slightly deleterious, compensatory mutations may occur to restabilize residue-residue interactions.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] This early work used what are known as *local* methods to calculate correlated mutations from protein sequences, but suffered from indirect false correlations which result from treating each pair of residues as independent of all other pairs.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] In 2011, a different, and this time *global* statistical approach, demonstrated that predicted coevolved residues were sufficient to predict the 3D fold of a protein, providing there are enough sequences available (>1,000 homologous sequences are needed).
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The method, EVfold, uses no homology modeling, threading or 3D structure fragments and can be run on a standard personal computer even for proteins with hundreds of residues.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The accuracy of the contacts predicted using this and related approaches has now been demonstrated on many known structures and contact maps, including the prediction of experimentally unsolved transmembrane proteins.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Comparative protein modeling uses previously solved structures as starting points, or templates.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] This is effective because it appears that although the number of actual proteins is vast, there is a limited set of tertiary structural motifs to which most proteins belong.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] It has been suggested that there are only around 2,000 distinct protein folds in nature, though there are many millions of different proteins.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The comparative protein modeling can combine with the evolutionary covariation in the structure prediction.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Accurate packing of the amino acid side chains represents a separate problem in protein structure prediction.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Methods that specifically address the problem of predicting side-chain geometry include dead-end elimination and the self-consistent mean field methods.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The side chain conformations with low energy are usually determined on the rigid polypeptide backbone and using a set of discrete side chain conformations known as "rotamers".
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The methods attempt to identify the set of rotamers that minimize the model's overall energy.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] These methods use rotamer libraries, which are collections of favorable conformations for each residue type in proteins.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Rotamer libraries may contain information about the conformation, its frequency, and the standard deviations about mean dihedral angles, which can be used in sampling.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Rotamer libraries are derived from structural bioinformatics or other statistical analysis of side-chain conformations in known experimental structures of proteins, such as by clustering the observed conformations for tetrahedral carbons near the staggered (60°, 180°, −60°) values.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Rotamer libraries can be backbone-independent, secondary-structure-dependent, or backbone-dependent.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Backbone-independent rotamer libraries make no reference to backbone conformation, and are calculated from all available side chains of a certain type (for instance, the first example of a rotamer library, done by Ponder and Richards at Yale in 1987).
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Secondary-structure-dependent libraries present different dihedral angles and/or rotamer frequencies for $\alpha$ -helix, $\beta$ -sheet, or coil secondary structures.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Backbone-dependent rotamer libraries present conformations and/or frequencies dependent on the local backbone conformation as defined by the backbone dihedral angles $\phi$ and $\psi$ , regardless of secondary structure.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The modern versions of these libraries as used in most software are presented as multidimensional distributions of probability or frequency, where the peaks correspond to the dihedral-angle conformations considered as individual rotamers in the lists.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Some versions are based on very carefully curated data and are used primarily for structure validation, while others emphasize relative frequencies in much larger data sets and are the form used primarily for structure prediction, such as the Dunbrack rotamer libraries.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] In the case of complexes of two or more proteins, where the structures of the proteins are known or can be predicted with high accuracy, protein–protein docking methods can be used to predict the structure of the complex.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Information of the effect of mutations at specific sites on the affinity of the complex helps to understand the complex structure and to guide docking methods.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] A great number of software tools for protein structure prediction exist.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Approaches include homology modeling, protein threading, *ab initio* methods, secondary structure prediction, and transmembrane helix and signal peptide prediction.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] In particular, deep learning based on long short-term memory has been used for this purpose since 2007, when it was successfully applied to protein homology detection and to predict subcellular localization of proteins.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Some recent successful methods based on the CASP experiments include I-TASSER, HHpred and AlphaFold.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] In 2021, AlphaFold was reported to perform best.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Knowing the structure of a protein often allows functional prediction as well.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] For instance, collagen is folded into a long-extended fiber-like chain and it makes it a fibrous protein.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Recently, several techniques have been developed to predict protein folding and thus protein structure, for example, Itasser, and AlphaFold.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] AlphaFold was one of the first AIs to predict protein structures.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] It was introduced by Google's DeepMind in the 13th CASP competition, which was held in 2018.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] AlphaFold relies on a neural network approach, which directly predicts the 3D coordinates of all non-hydrogen atoms for a given protein using the amino acid sequence and aligned homologous sequences.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The AlphaFold network consists of a trunk which processes the inputs through repeated layers, and a structure module which introduces an explicit 3D structure.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Earlier neural networks for protein structure prediction used LSTM.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Since AlphaFold outputs protein coordinates directly, AlphaFold produces predictions in graphics processing unit (GPU) minutes to GPU hours, depending on the length of protein sequence.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The European Bioinformatics Institute together with DeepMind have constructed the AlphaFold – EBI database for predicted protein structures.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] AlphaFold2, was introduced in CASP14, and is capable of predicting protein structures to near experimental accuracy.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] AlphaFold was swiftly followed by RoseTTAFold and later by OmegaFold and the ESM Metagenomic Atlas.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] 2022 demonstrated the application of protein structure prediction in genome annotation, specifically in identifying functional protein isoforms using computationally predicted structures, available at https://www.isoform.io.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] This study highlights the promise of protein structure prediction as a genome annotation tool and presents a practical, structure-guided approach that can be used to enhance the annotation of any genome.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] In 2024, David Baker and Demis Hassabis (along with John M.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Jumper) were awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry for their contributions to computational protein modeling, including the development of AlphaFold2, an AI-based model for protein structure prediction.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] AlphaFold2's accuracy has been evaluated against experimentally determined protein structures using metrics such as root-mean-square deviation (RMSD).
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The median RMSD between different experimental structures of the same protein is approximately 0.6 Å, while the median RMSD between AlphaFold2 predictions and experimental structures is around 1 Å.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] For regions where AlphaFold2 assigns high confidence, the median RMSD is about 0.6 Å, comparable to the variability observed between different experimental structures.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] However, in low-confidence regions, the RMSD can exceed 2 Å, indicating greater deviations.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] In proteins with multiple domains connected by flexible linkers, AlphaFold2 predicts individual domain structures accurately but may assign random relative positions to these domains.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] Additionally, AlphaFold2 does not account for structural constraints such as the membrane plane, sometimes placing protein domains in positions that would physically clash with the membrane.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] CASP, which stands for Critical Assessment of Techniques for Protein Structure Prediction, is a community-wide experiment for protein structure prediction taking place every two years since 1994.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] CASP provides with an opportunity to assess the quality of available human, non-automated methodology (human category) and automatic servers for protein structure prediction (server category, introduced in the CASP7).
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] The CAMEO3D Continuous Automated Model EvaluatiOn Server evaluates automated protein structure prediction servers on a weekly basis using blind predictions for newly release protein structures.
[src:protein-folding/protein-structure-prediction] CAMEO publishes the results on its website.
